ABUJA – A United States agency and global provider of weath­er intelligence, Earth Net­works, and Nigerian Meteo­rological Agency (NiMet) on Wednesday inaugurated ear­ly warning severe lightning equipment across airports in Nigeria. Speaking during a kick-off ceremony of equipment installation in Abuja, Prof. Mansur Bako Matazu, the Director General and Chief Executive Officer of NiMet, said the deal resulted from a formal request on the 18 August 2021, for the signing of Memorandum of Under­standing (MoU) between NiMet and Earth Network for collaboration. The NiMet boss said objec­tive of the collaboration was to support the capacity of NiMet to develop its service offerings/delivery through working together to deploy EN Stations in various loca­tions that will contribute to the Nigeria Total Lightning and Mesoscale AWS Network (NTLMAN) and enable EN forecasting services (ENcast). -Advertisement- He said the installation of the equipment was combined with capacity building for NiMet officers, stressing that NiMet was not only getting equipment donation, but was also building capacity of its staff. “Under the supervision and guidance of our EN ex­perts, Abuja, Benin and Lagos will be covered Thereafter, NiMet officers equipped with the skills acquired will carry out the remaining installa­tions,” he said. Matazu said the collabo­ration would help NiMet in preparing and interpreting government policy in the field of meteorology; and also issuing weather (and climate) forecasts for safe operation of aircrafts, ocean going vessels and oil rigs and other socio­economic sectors, including disaster risk reduction. On his part, Jean Blasé Ngameni, the West Africa representative for Earth Network, assured NIMET that the partnership would promote the best weather and lightning observation network.